), {{ill|Kunini-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|ja|国之常立尊|lt=Kunini-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunini-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|qq=}} and {{ill|Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kunikazutsu-no-Mikoto|ja|国狭槌尊|lt=Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kunikazutsu-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunikazutsu-no-Mikoto|qq=}} are followed by the third deity, {{ill|Toyoshinrei-no-Mikoto|ja|豊斟渟尊|lt=Toyoshinrei-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyoshinrei-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, who is noted as a male deity. In the first volume, the '''Nihon Shoki''' (『日本書紀』) identifies the third deity after {{ill|Kunini-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|ja|国之常立尊|lt=Kunini-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunini-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|qq=}} and {{ill|Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kunikazutsu-no-Mikoto|ja|国狭槌尊|lt=Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kunikazutsu-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunikazutsu-no-Mikoto|qq=}} as '''Toyokunushi-no-Mikoto''' (豊国主尊), also known by aliases '''Toyogumi-no-Mikoto''' (豊組野尊), '''Toyokabushino-Mikoto''' (豊香節野尊), '''Ukakeyuyami-no-Mikoto''' (浮経野豊買尊), '''Toyokuni-no-Mikoto''' (豊国野尊), '''Toyoneguchi-no-Mikoto''' (豊齧野尊), '''Hagikuni-no-Mikoto''' (葉木国野尊), '''Mikonomi-no-Mikoto''' (国見野尊), and '''Minono-Mikoto''' (見野尊). The prevalence of names starting with "豊" (豊, "toyoo" meaning "abundant") suggests that Toyokumono-no-Kami and Toyoshinrei-no-Mikoto are manifestations of the same deity. In volumes two through six, names believed to refer to the same deity do not appear. Neither the '''Kojiki''' (『古事記』) nor the '''Nihon Shoki''' (『日本書紀』) mention Toyokumono-no-Mikoto in later myths. == Shrines Enshrining Toyokumono-no-Mikoto == * {{ill|Mononobe Shrine|ja|物部神社|lt=Monobe Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mononobe Shrine|qq=}} – within the precincts, {{ill|Jinsei Shichidai Shrine|ja|神代七代社|lt=Jinsei Shichidai Shr